Data Description

The file “MPG.csv” contains data adapted from a dataset donated by StatLib library (Carnegie Mellon University) on https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/. The original data was composed on July 7, 1993 and was referenced to the following paper: Quinlan,R. (1993). Combining Instance-Based and Model-Based Learning. In Proceedings on the Tenth International Conference of Machine Learning, 236-243, University of Massachusetts, Amherst. Morgan Kaufmann.

This dataset is about a sample of 398 automobiles, descripting the relationships among mpg and the following variables:

  1. mpg: miles per gallon index of each vehicle;

  2. cylinders: number of cylinders of each vehicle;

  3. displacement: displacement of each vehicle in kilo-miles;

  4. horsepower: horsepower of each vehicle relevant to;

  5. weight: weight of each vehicle in pound;

  6. acceleration: seconds of each vehicle accelerates from 0 mph to 60 mph;

  7. model year: year the car was made in yy

  8. origin: Location of manufacture (1 - America; 2 - Europe; 3 - Asia)

  9. car name: name of the car band and model

According to the residual versus fitted value plot, the assumptions on linearity, equal variance, and normality of errors seem to be violated. Therefore, transform both response and predictors.

lm_full1=lm(log(mpg$mpg)~mpg$displacement+mpg$horsepower+(mpg$weight)^2+mpg$acceleration+mpg$model.year+orig)
plot(lm_full1)

We addressed non-linearity and non-constant variance of errors by transforming variables. However, we will investigate for the outliers that have strong influence on model.

residuals=lm_full1$residuals
sigma_hat=summary(lm_full1)$sigma
X1=model.matrix(log(mpg$mpg)~mpg$displacement+mpg$horsepower+(mpg$weight)^2+mpg$acceleration+mpg$model.year+orig)
H=X1%*%solve(t(X1)%*%X1)%*%t(X1)
h=diag(H)
r=residuals/(sigma_hat*sqrt(1-h))
p=8
sum(h)
## [1] 8
n=nrow(mpg)
thresh2=2*p/n
thresh3=3*p/n
plot(h,xlab='Observation #',ylab='leverage',main='Leverage')
abline(h=thresh2,lty=2,col='red')
abline(h=thresh3,lty=2,col='blue')

which(h>thresh3)
##  14  28  29 389 
##  14  28  29 389
t=r*sqrt((n-p-1)/(n-p-r^2))
plot(t,xlab="Observation #",ylab="Studentized residuals",main="Studentized residuals")

which(abs(t)>3)
## 111 124 165 
## 111 124 165

According to the leverage and cook’s distnace, we can check that the 14th observation is an outlier that influence the model. Therefore, we delete the 14th observation from the data set.

mpg1=mpg[-c(14),]

With the new data set, create the new model lm_full2 and check for multicollinearities.

orig1=factor(mpg1$origin)

Since the residual versus fitted plot suggests that the assumptions on errors are now held, we move forward to stepwise model selection.
